"Foufopoulos J., Kilpatrick A.M., Ives A.R.","Climate change and elevated extinction rates of reptiles from Mediterranean islands",2011,"American Naturalist","177","1",,"119","129",,,10.1086/657624,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-78650873099&partnerID=40&md5=c5ae708a5c238f4e13e110a2cd0c9b46","School of Natural Resources and Environment, University of Michigan, Ann Arbor MI 48109, United States; Department of Zoology, University of Wisconsin, Madison, WI 53706, United States; Consortium for Conservation Medicine, 460 West 34th Street, New York, NY 10001, United States; Department of Ecology and Evolutionary Biology, University of California, Santa Cruz, CA 95064, United States","Foufopoulos, J., School of Natural Resources and Environment, University of Michigan, Ann Arbor MI 48109, United States, Department of Zoology, University of Wisconsin, Madison, WI 53706, United States; Kilpatrick, A.M., Department of Zoology, University of Wisconsin, Madison, WI 53706, United States, Consortium for Conservation Medicine, 460 West 34th Street, New York, NY 10001, United States; Ives, A.R., Department of Zoology, University of Wisconsin, Madison, WI 53706, United States, Department of Ecology and Evolutionary Biology, University of California, Santa Cruz, CA 95064, United States","Recent climate change has caused the distributions of many species to shift poleward, yet few empirical studies have addressed which species will be vulnerable to longer-term climate changes. To investigate past consequences of climate change, we calculated the population extinction rates of 35 reptile species from 87 Greek land-bridge islands in the Mediterranean that occurred over the past 16,000 years. Population extinction rates were higher for those species that today have more northern distributions. We further found that northern species requiring cool, mesic habitats had less available suitable habitat among islands, implicating loss of suitable habitat in their elevated extinction rates. These extinctions occurred in the context of increasing habitat fragmentation, with islands shrinking and separating as sea levels rose. Thus, the circumstances faced by reptiles on the islands are similar to challenges for numerous species today that must cope with a changing climate while living in an increasingly human-fragmented landscape. Our island-biogeographical approach to investigating historical population extinctions gives insight into the long-term patterns of species responses to climate change. © 2010 by The University of Chicago.","Aegean Sea; Conservation; Faunal relaxation; Global warming.; Herpetology; Island biogeography","biogeography; empirical analysis; extinction risk; global warming; habitat conservation; habitat fragmentation; habitat type; land bridge; physiological response; population distribution; reptile; sea level change; species diversity; vulnerability; animal; article; classification; climate change; Greece; phylogeny; physiology; reptile; species extinction; Animals; Climate Change; Extinction, Biological; Greece; Phylogeny; Reptiles; Aegean Sea; Mediterranean Region; Mediterranean Sea; Reptilia",,,,,,"Bachmayer, F., Brinkerink, J.H., Symeonidis, N., Pleistozäne Schildkröten aus Höhlen der Insel Kreta (1975) Annales Geologiques des Pays Helleniques, 27, pp. 110-122; Beutler, A., (1981) Cyrtodactylus Kotschyi, 1, pp. 53-74. , (Steindachner, 1870)- Ägäischer Bogenfingergecko, in W. Böhme, ed. Handbuch der Reptilien und Amphibien Europas. AULA, Wiesbaden; Böhme, W., (1981) Handbuch der Amphibien und Reptilien Europas, 6. , AULA, Wiesbaden; Bottema, S., Sarpaki, A., Environmental change in Crete: A 9000-year record of Holocene vegetation history and the effect of the Santorini eruption (2003) Holocene, 13, pp. 733-749; Burkey, T.V., Extinction rates in archipelagoes: Implications for populations in fragmented habitats (1995) Conservation Biology, 9, pp. 527-541; Calsbeek, R., Smith, T.B., Ocean currents mediate evolut